### React 19 Features

React 19 introduced major new features including async server components, improved hooks, and a new compiler.

---

### React Compiler (React Forget)

React 19 includes an optimizing compiler that automatically memoizes components and hooks:

```jsx
// No need for manual useMemo/useCallback - compiler handles it
function Profile({ user, posts }) {
  const filtered = posts.filter(p => p.authorId === user.id);
  return <List items={filtered} />;
}
```

### Server Components

Server Components run exclusively on the server, reducing client bundle size:

```jsx
// ServerComponent.server.js
async function ProductList() {
  const products = await db.products.findAll();
  return (
    <ul>
      {products.map(p => <li key={p.id}>{p.name}</li>)}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

### New Hooks in React 19

| Hook | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `use()` | Reads resources (promises, context) inside render |
| `useActionState` | Manages form submission state |
| `useFormStatus` | Provides form submission status to descendants |
| `useOptimistic` | Optimistic UI updates |

### The `use()` Hook

```jsx
import { use } from 'react';

function Comments({ commentsPromise }) {
  const comments = use(commentsPromise);
  return comments.map(c => <p key={c.id}>{c.text}</p>);
}
```

### Improved `<form>` Actions

```jsx
<form action={async (formData) => {
  await submitToServer(formData);
}}>
  <input name="email" type="email" />
  <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>
```

> **Key Point:** React 19 focuses on performance (compiler), data loading (server components, use()), and form handling (actions, useActionState). The compiler eliminates the need for manual memoization.

codeExample:
import { use, Suspense } from 'react';

function fetchUser(id) {
  return fetch(`/api/users/${id}`).then(r => r.json());
}

function UserProfile({ userId }) {
  const userPromise = useMemo(() => fetchUser(userId), [userId]);

  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<p>Loading user...</p>}>
      <UserDetails userPromise={userPromise} />
    </Suspense>
  );
}

function UserDetails({ userPromise }) {
  const user = use(userPromise);
  return <h1>{user.name}</h1>;
}
